{"questionId":"19783","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The water temperature <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>)</mo></math> in Lake Windermere is measured on the first day of eight&nbsp;consecutive months <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>)</mo></math> from January to August (months <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn></math>) and the results are shown&nbsp;below. The value for May (month <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>) has been accidently deleted.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/5573a504d6449e0b54c97ef52754c0732073c284.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Explain why your line should not be used to estimate the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> at which&nbsp;the temperature is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" class=\"wrs_chemistry\"><mo>°</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Because the line should only be used to estimate <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> and not <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math>. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>R1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[1 mark]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19783","referenceCode":"EXN.1.SL.TZ0.8c.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Explain why your line should not be used to estimate the value of m at which the temperature is 10.0 °C.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}